The '''''Marshal Ney''''' was a class of [[Monitor (warship)|monitor]] built for the [[Royal Navy]] during the [[World War I|First World War]].
==Design and development== The need for monitors for shelling enemy positions from the [[English Channel]] had become apparent only at the start of the war and they were designed with some haste. The design of monitors had been given by the [[Director of Naval Construction]], [[Sir Eustace Tennyson d'Eyncourt, 1st Baronet|Eustace Tennyson d'Eyncourt]], to the Assistant Constructor, [[Charles S. Lillicrap]] (later himself to become Director). By the time the ''Marshal Ney''s came about some 33 monitors of various sorts had already been ordered. The redesign of the battlecruisers {{HMS|Renown|1916|2}} and {{HMS|Repulse|1916|2}} meant that there were now two modern 15-inch turrets available. The [[First Sea Lord]] [[John Fisher, 1st Baron Fisher|Jackie Fisher]] and [[Winston Churchill]], [[First Lord of the Admiralty]] decided these should be used for two more monitors, initially ''M 13'' and ''M 14'', but then renamed after the French [[Napoleonic War]] [[Marshal of France|marshal]]s [[Nicolas Jean de Dieu Soult]] and [[Michel Ney]].
For machinery the two monitors received [[diesel engine]]s, which were then a novelty – the majority of ships being steam powered. The use of diesels meant that they had no need of boiler rooms which went well with a low draught, nor of large funnels which reduced the amount of superstructure. These engines were originally designed for much smaller freighters and therefore they proved particularly slow and unreliable.
The turret was on multi-sided [[barbette]] made of individual flat plates, cutting down on the build time. The {{convert|4|in|mm|0|adj=on}} guns were disposed along her sides for protection from smaller vessels, the {{convert|3|in|mm|0|adj=on}} guns being for anti-aircraft use.
==Ships==
* [[HMS Marshal Soult|''Marshal Soult'']] :Built by [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company Limited|Palmers]], Newcastle :Launched June 1915 :Completed August 1915 :Served with the Dover Monitor Squadron, after the war became a gunnery training ship. At the start of World War II she was considered for recommissioning but instead her turret was removed for a new monitor, [[HMS Abercrombie (F109)|''Abercrombie'']] and she became a headquarters ship. She was paid off and scrapped in 1946 * [[HMS Marshal Ney|''Marshal Ney'']] :Built by [[Palmers Shipbuilding and Iron Company Limited|Palmers]], Newcastle :Launched August 1915 :Completed November 1915 :After trials the turret was removed for [[HMS Erebus (I02)|''Erebus'']] and she was regunned with 6- and {{convert|4|in|mm|0|sing=on}} guns and acted as a guardship until the end of the war. She later acted as a depot ship gaining onshore buildings, and was renamed ''Alaunia II'' and was only finally scrapped in 1957
